</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Gastroesophageal reflux disease (GERD) is a common condition and impairs the quality of life for millions of patients, accounts for considerable health care spending, and is a primary risk factor for esophageal adenocarcinoma. There have been substantial advances in understanding the pathogenesis of GERD and its complications and much progress in diagnosis and management of GERD; however, these have not been comprehensively discussed in the recent radiology literature. Understanding the role of imaging in GERD and its complications is important to aid in multidisciplinary treatment of GERD. GERD results from prolonged or recurrent reflux of gastric contents into the esophagus. Common symptoms include heartburn or regurgitation. Prolonged reflux of gastric contents into the esophagus can cause erosive esophagitis. Over time, the inflammatory response related to esophagitis can lead to deposition of fibrous tissue and development of strictures. Alternatively, the esophageal mucosa can undergo metaplasia (Barrett esophagus), a precursor to dysplasia (which can lead to adenocarcinoma). Conventional barium esophagography has long been considered the primary imaging modality for the esophagus, and the fluoroscopic findings for diagnosis of GERD have been well established. Multimodality imaging has a clear role in detection and assessment of the complications of GERD, specifically reflux esophagitis and Barrett esophagus; differentiation of benign and malignant strictures; and detection, staging, and posttreatment surveillance of esophageal adenocarcinoma. Given the dramatic changes in utilization of abdominal imaging during the past 2 decades, with significantly declining volume of fluoroscopic procedures and concomitant increase in CT and MRI studies, it is crucial that modern radiologists appreciate the value of barium esophagography in the workup of GERD and recognize the key imaging features of GERD and its complications at CT and MRI.</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190029">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.2020190029">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig1.jpeg" height="2640" width="3589" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span>. Normal anatomy and histologic features of the esophagus and esophagogastric junction (EGJ). The esophagus is anatomically divided into three segments: The cervical segment extends between the bony landmarks of the cricoid cartilage and sternal notch, the thoracic segment extends between the sternal notch and diaphragm, and the abdominal segment extends between the diaphragm and EGJ. The EGJ is histologically defined as the junction between the squamous epithelium–lined esophagus and the columnar epithelium–lined gastric cardia, also called the squamocolumnar junction. The esophageal mucosa is composed of stratified squamous epithelium. (Reprinted, with permission, from Aletta Ann Frazier, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig2a.jpeg" height="1464" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig2a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the normal esophagus shows stratified squamous epithelium with a thin basal zone composed of proliferative cylindrical basophilic cells (white bracket); a central zone composed of multilayered, maturing, flattened, glycogen-rich cells (black bracket); and a surface composed of a few flattened cells devoid of nuclei (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic US image shows the multilayered appearance of the esophageal wall as alternating rings of echogenicity: hyperechoic superficial mucosa, hypoechoic deep mucosa (white arrowhead), hyperechoic submucosa, hypoechoic muscularis propria (black arrowhead), and hyperechoic adventitia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig2a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig2b.jpeg" height="1464" width="1617" aria-labelledby="fig2b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the normal esophagus shows stratified squamous epithelium with a thin basal zone composed of proliferative cylindrical basophilic cells (white bracket); a central zone composed of multilayered, maturing, flattened, glycogen-rich cells (black bracket); and a surface composed of a few flattened cells devoid of nuclei (arrow). (Hematoxylin-eosin [H-E] stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic US image shows the multilayered appearance of the esophageal wall as alternating rings of echogenicity: hyperechoic superficial mucosa, hypoechoic deep mucosa (white arrowhead), hyperechoic submucosa, hypoechoic muscularis propria (black arrowhead), and hyperechoic adventitia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig2b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig3a.jpeg" height="1423" width="1570" aria-labelledby="fig3a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a normal-thickness (&lt;5 mm) homogeneously enhancing esophageal wall (straight arrow) surrounding a small amount of intraluminal air, with a distinct surrounding fat plane (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> In-phase T1-weighted MR image shows the normal esophagus as a collapsed tubular structure of homogeneous low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase T1-weighted image shows the distinct margin between the outer esophageal wall (straight arrow) and surrounding fat (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image from volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) imaging shows normal wall thickness with homogeneous mural enhancement (arrow). <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted image shows the multilayered appearance of the normal esophagus, with the normal mucosa seen as a thin layer of intermediate signal intensity (white arrowhead) surrounded by an outer thin layer of low-signal-intensity muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig3a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig3b.jpeg" height="1423" width="1573" aria-labelledby="fig3b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a normal-thickness (&lt;5 mm) homogeneously enhancing esophageal wall (straight arrow) surrounding a small amount of intraluminal air, with a distinct surrounding fat plane (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> In-phase T1-weighted MR image shows the normal esophagus as a collapsed tubular structure of homogeneous low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase T1-weighted image shows the distinct margin between the outer esophageal wall (straight arrow) and surrounding fat (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image from volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) imaging shows normal wall thickness with homogeneous mural enhancement (arrow). <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted image shows the multilayered appearance of the normal esophagus, with the normal mucosa seen as a thin layer of intermediate signal intensity (white arrowhead) surrounded by an outer thin layer of low-signal-intensity muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig3b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig3c.jpeg" height="1425" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig3c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a normal-thickness (&lt;5 mm) homogeneously enhancing esophageal wall (straight arrow) surrounding a small amount of intraluminal air, with a distinct surrounding fat plane (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> In-phase T1-weighted MR image shows the normal esophagus as a collapsed tubular structure of homogeneous low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase T1-weighted image shows the distinct margin between the outer esophageal wall (straight arrow) and surrounding fat (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image from volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) imaging shows normal wall thickness with homogeneous mural enhancement (arrow). <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted image shows the multilayered appearance of the normal esophagus, with the normal mucosa seen as a thin layer of intermediate signal intensity (white arrowhead) surrounded by an outer thin layer of low-signal-intensity muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig3c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig3d.jpeg" height="1425" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig3d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3d</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a normal-thickness (&lt;5 mm) homogeneously enhancing esophageal wall (straight arrow) surrounding a small amount of intraluminal air, with a distinct surrounding fat plane (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> In-phase T1-weighted MR image shows the normal esophagus as a collapsed tubular structure of homogeneous low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase T1-weighted image shows the distinct margin between the outer esophageal wall (straight arrow) and surrounding fat (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image from volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) imaging shows normal wall thickness with homogeneous mural enhancement (arrow). <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted image shows the multilayered appearance of the normal esophagus, with the normal mucosa seen as a thin layer of intermediate signal intensity (white arrowhead) surrounded by an outer thin layer of low-signal-intensity muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig3d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3e" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig3e.jpeg" height="1357" width="1499" aria-labelledby="fig3e" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3e</span>. Normal esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT image shows a normal-thickness (&lt;5 mm) homogeneously enhancing esophageal wall (straight arrow) surrounding a small amount of intraluminal air, with a distinct surrounding fat plane (curved arrow). <b>(b)</b> In-phase T1-weighted MR image shows the normal esophagus as a collapsed tubular structure of homogeneous low signal intensity (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase T1-weighted image shows the distinct margin between the outer esophageal wall (straight arrow) and surrounding fat (curved arrow). <b>(d)</b> Contrast-enhanced T1-weighted image from volumetric interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) imaging shows normal wall thickness with homogeneous mural enhancement (arrow). <b>(e)</b> T2-weighted image shows the multilayered appearance of the normal esophagus, with the normal mucosa seen as a thin layer of intermediate signal intensity (white arrowhead) surrounded by an outer thin layer of low-signal-intensity muscularis propria (black arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig3e">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig4a.jpeg" height="1317" width="1189" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span>. Multimodality appearance of the EGJ. The LES is defined functionally and is difficult to precisely identify anatomically, radiographically, and endoscopically. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of gross specimen of EGJ shows transition from the tan-white esophageal squamous mucosa to the velvet red columnar mucosa of the gastric cardia (arrow), but there is no focal muscular thickening in the relaxed state to anatomically denote the location of the LES. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the normal EGJ shows thin longitudinal vessels visible through the squamous epithelium. Endoscopically, the EGJ can be defined as the lower limit of the longitudinal vessels. <b>(c)</b> Single-contrast esophagram shows contrast material distending the distal esophagus, with tapering of the lower esophagus in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the LES (arrow) and with contrast material and air filling the gastric cardia and fundus. During swallowing, the LES relaxes, allowing the contrast material bolus to pass through the EGJ (arrow) into the stomach. <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows the anatomy of the distal esophagus and EGJ. There is focal widening of the relaxed LES compared with the esophageal body (referred to as the ampulla or vestibule), and the inferior edge of the ampulla represents the EGJ (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig4b.jpeg" height="1318" width="1457" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span>. Multimodality appearance of the EGJ. The LES is defined functionally and is difficult to precisely identify anatomically, radiographically, and endoscopically. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of gross specimen of EGJ shows transition from the tan-white esophageal squamous mucosa to the velvet red columnar mucosa of the gastric cardia (arrow), but there is no focal muscular thickening in the relaxed state to anatomically denote the location of the LES. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the normal EGJ shows thin longitudinal vessels visible through the squamous epithelium. Endoscopically, the EGJ can be defined as the lower limit of the longitudinal vessels. <b>(c)</b> Single-contrast esophagram shows contrast material distending the distal esophagus, with tapering of the lower esophagus in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the LES (arrow) and with contrast material and air filling the gastric cardia and fundus. During swallowing, the LES relaxes, allowing the contrast material bolus to pass through the EGJ (arrow) into the stomach. <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows the anatomy of the distal esophagus and EGJ. There is focal widening of the relaxed LES compared with the esophageal body (referred to as the ampulla or vestibule), and the inferior edge of the ampulla represents the EGJ (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig4c.jpeg" height="1524" width="962" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span>. Multimodality appearance of the EGJ. The LES is defined functionally and is difficult to precisely identify anatomically, radiographically, and endoscopically. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of gross specimen of EGJ shows transition from the tan-white esophageal squamous mucosa to the velvet red columnar mucosa of the gastric cardia (arrow), but there is no focal muscular thickening in the relaxed state to anatomically denote the location of the LES. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the normal EGJ shows thin longitudinal vessels visible through the squamous epithelium. Endoscopically, the EGJ can be defined as the lower limit of the longitudinal vessels. <b>(c)</b> Single-contrast esophagram shows contrast material distending the distal esophagus, with tapering of the lower esophagus in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the LES (arrow) and with contrast material and air filling the gastric cardia and fundus. During swallowing, the LES relaxes, allowing the contrast material bolus to pass through the EGJ (arrow) into the stomach. <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows the anatomy of the distal esophagus and EGJ. There is focal widening of the relaxed LES compared with the esophageal body (referred to as the ampulla or vestibule), and the inferior edge of the ampulla represents the EGJ (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig4d.jpeg" height="1524" width="1686" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span>. Multimodality appearance of the EGJ. The LES is defined functionally and is difficult to precisely identify anatomically, radiographically, and endoscopically. <b>(a)</b> Photograph of gross specimen of EGJ shows transition from the tan-white esophageal squamous mucosa to the velvet red columnar mucosa of the gastric cardia (arrow), but there is no focal muscular thickening in the relaxed state to anatomically denote the location of the LES. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image of the normal EGJ shows thin longitudinal vessels visible through the squamous epithelium. Endoscopically, the EGJ can be defined as the lower limit of the longitudinal vessels. <b>(c)</b> Single-contrast esophagram shows contrast material distending the distal esophagus, with tapering of the lower esophagus in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the LES (arrow) and with contrast material and air filling the gastric cardia and fundus. During swallowing, the LES relaxes, allowing the contrast material bolus to pass through the EGJ (arrow) into the stomach. <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique CT image shows the anatomy of the distal esophagus and EGJ. There is focal widening of the relaxed LES compared with the esophageal body (referred to as the ampulla or vestibule), and the inferior edge of the ampulla represents the EGJ (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig5a.jpeg" height="1785" width="1428" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span>. Measurement devices for assessment of GERD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal radiograph of the chest shows a small ovoid foreign body (arrow), which represents a wireless esophageal monitoring device, projecting over the midline posterior mediastinum in the expected location of the middistal esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a Bravo capsule. (Reprinted, with permission, from Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn.) <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows a radiopaque intraesophageal wireless pH probe (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig5b.jpeg" height="1785" width="652" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span>. Measurement devices for assessment of GERD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal radiograph of the chest shows a small ovoid foreign body (arrow), which represents a wireless esophageal monitoring device, projecting over the midline posterior mediastinum in the expected location of the middistal esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a Bravo capsule. (Reprinted, with permission, from Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn.) <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows a radiopaque intraesophageal wireless pH probe (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig5c.jpeg" height="1785" width="1614" aria-labelledby="fig5c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span>. Measurement devices for assessment of GERD. <b>(a)</b> Frontal radiograph of the chest shows a small ovoid foreign body (arrow), which represents a wireless esophageal monitoring device, projecting over the midline posterior mediastinum in the expected location of the middistal esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Photograph shows a Bravo capsule. (Reprinted, with permission, from Medtronic, Minneapolis, Minn.) <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image shows a radiopaque intraesophageal wireless pH probe (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig5c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig6a.jpeg" height="2099" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span>. Hiatal hernia. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast esophagram shows cephalic displacement of the tapered EGJ (arrow) above the level of the diaphragm. Note the gastric folds within the hernia. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows a large hiatal hernia (arrow). Smaller hernias are more difficult to reliably identify with endoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig6b.jpeg" height="1167" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span>. Hiatal hernia. <b>(a)</b> Double-contrast esophagram shows cephalic displacement of the tapered EGJ (arrow) above the level of the diaphragm. Note the gastric folds within the hernia. <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows a large hiatal hernia (arrow). Smaller hernias are more difficult to reliably identify with endoscopy.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig7a.jpeg" height="1416" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span>. Hiatal hernia at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image without oral contrast material shows a homogeneous well-circumscribed mass (arrow) in the inferior posterior mediastinum, which exerts mass effect on the left heart. <b>(b)</b> Subsequent CT image with oral contrast material shows gas and contrast material distending the mass (arrow), confirming it to be a moderate hiatal hernia. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image through the midline shows cephalic displacement of the EGJ (curved arrow) and gastric cardia (straight arrow) above the diaphragm. The distal esophagus is incompletely distended with contrast material (*). <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image after Nissen fundoplication shows a short segment of the gastric fundus around the distal esophagus (arrows), reinforcing the EGJ to restore the physiologic equivalent of the normal LES.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig7b.jpeg" height="1416" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span>. Hiatal hernia at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image without oral contrast material shows a homogeneous well-circumscribed mass (arrow) in the inferior posterior mediastinum, which exerts mass effect on the left heart. <b>(b)</b> Subsequent CT image with oral contrast material shows gas and contrast material distending the mass (arrow), confirming it to be a moderate hiatal hernia. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image through the midline shows cephalic displacement of the EGJ (curved arrow) and gastric cardia (straight arrow) above the diaphragm. The distal esophagus is incompletely distended with contrast material (*). <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image after Nissen fundoplication shows a short segment of the gastric fundus around the distal esophagus (arrows), reinforcing the EGJ to restore the physiologic equivalent of the normal LES.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig7c.jpeg" height="1296" width="1320" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span>. Hiatal hernia at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image without oral contrast material shows a homogeneous well-circumscribed mass (arrow) in the inferior posterior mediastinum, which exerts mass effect on the left heart. <b>(b)</b> Subsequent CT image with oral contrast material shows gas and contrast material distending the mass (arrow), confirming it to be a moderate hiatal hernia. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image through the midline shows cephalic displacement of the EGJ (curved arrow) and gastric cardia (straight arrow) above the diaphragm. The distal esophagus is incompletely distended with contrast material (*). <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image after Nissen fundoplication shows a short segment of the gastric fundus around the distal esophagus (arrows), reinforcing the EGJ to restore the physiologic equivalent of the normal LES.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig7d.jpeg" height="1296" width="1432" aria-labelledby="fig7d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7d</span>. Hiatal hernia at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image without oral contrast material shows a homogeneous well-circumscribed mass (arrow) in the inferior posterior mediastinum, which exerts mass effect on the left heart. <b>(b)</b> Subsequent CT image with oral contrast material shows gas and contrast material distending the mass (arrow), confirming it to be a moderate hiatal hernia. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal CT image through the midline shows cephalic displacement of the EGJ (curved arrow) and gastric cardia (straight arrow) above the diaphragm. The distal esophagus is incompletely distended with contrast material (*). <b>(d)</b> Coronal oblique maximum intensity projection (MIP) CT image after Nissen fundoplication shows a short segment of the gastric fundus around the distal esophagus (arrows), reinforcing the EGJ to restore the physiologic equivalent of the normal LES.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig7d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig8a.jpeg" height="1875" width="1500" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span>. Surgically placed magnetic device to augment the LES. <b>(a)</b> Frontal radiograph shows a ring of round metallic beads (arrow) in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the EGJ. With swallowing, the pressure associated with the propelled bolus opens the ring, with widening of the space between the magnetic beads. <b>(b)</b> Upright double-contrast esophagram shows widening of the space between the magnetic beads (arrow). <b>(c)</b> CT image reconstructed in the coronal oblique plane to better demonstrate the EGJ shows the metallic areas of attenuation with associated streak artifact (arrow). Note the distal esophageal wall thickening (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig8b.jpeg" height="1466" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span>. Surgically placed magnetic device to augment the LES. <b>(a)</b> Frontal radiograph shows a ring of round metallic beads (arrow) in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the EGJ. With swallowing, the pressure associated with the propelled bolus opens the ring, with widening of the space between the magnetic beads. <b>(b)</b> Upright double-contrast esophagram shows widening of the space between the magnetic beads (arrow). <b>(c)</b> CT image reconstructed in the coronal oblique plane to better demonstrate the EGJ shows the metallic areas of attenuation with associated streak artifact (arrow). Note the distal esophageal wall thickening (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig8c.jpeg" height="1463" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig8c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8c</span>. Surgically placed magnetic device to augment the LES. <b>(a)</b> Frontal radiograph shows a ring of round metallic beads (arrow) in the expected subdiaphragmatic location of the EGJ. With swallowing, the pressure associated with the propelled bolus opens the ring, with widening of the space between the magnetic beads. <b>(b)</b> Upright double-contrast esophagram shows widening of the space between the magnetic beads (arrow). <b>(c)</b> CT image reconstructed in the coronal oblique plane to better demonstrate the EGJ shows the metallic areas of attenuation with associated streak artifact (arrow). Note the distal esophageal wall thickening (*).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig8c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig9a.jpeg" height="1448" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows inflammatory and regenerative changes associated with reflux esophagitis, including inflammatory infiltrate (straight arrow), basal cell hyperplasia (curved arrow), and papillary elongation (bracket). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows reddened nodular mucosa with near-circumferential mucosal ulcers (*), consistent with grade D esophagitis in the Los Angeles classification. <b>(c)</b> Upright double-contrast radiograph shows granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa (arrow), which is confluent with the EGJ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig9b.jpeg" height="1318" width="1456" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows inflammatory and regenerative changes associated with reflux esophagitis, including inflammatory infiltrate (straight arrow), basal cell hyperplasia (curved arrow), and papillary elongation (bracket). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows reddened nodular mucosa with near-circumferential mucosal ulcers (*), consistent with grade D esophagitis in the Los Angeles classification. <b>(c)</b> Upright double-contrast radiograph shows granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa (arrow), which is confluent with the EGJ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig9c.jpeg" height="1318" width="1193" aria-labelledby="fig9c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows inflammatory and regenerative changes associated with reflux esophagitis, including inflammatory infiltrate (straight arrow), basal cell hyperplasia (curved arrow), and papillary elongation (bracket). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Endoscopic image shows reddened nodular mucosa with near-circumferential mucosal ulcers (*), consistent with grade D esophagitis in the Los Angeles classification. <b>(c)</b> Upright double-contrast radiograph shows granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa (arrow), which is confluent with the EGJ.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig9c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig10a.jpeg" height="1334" width="1533" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows marked circumferential wall thickening (arrow), which is a nonspecific finding but correlates well with the presence of reflux esophagitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained with gaseous luminal distention better shows circumferential wall thickening with mucosal enhancement (arrow) and submucosal hypoenhancement (arrowhead), comprising the target sign, indicative of submucosal inflammation and edema. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image along the axis of the distal esophagus shows supradiaphragmatic positioning of the EGJ (straight arrow) with circumferential wall thickening of the distal esophageal wall, consistent with hiatal hernia and known reflux esophagitis. Note the presence of the target sign, composed of enhancing mucosa (curved arrow) and hypoenhancing submucosa (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Fast HASTE (half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo) T2-weighted image shows wall thickening of the distal esophagus (straight arrow) with high-signal-intensity mural edema (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig10b.jpeg" height="1334" width="1415" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows marked circumferential wall thickening (arrow), which is a nonspecific finding but correlates well with the presence of reflux esophagitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained with gaseous luminal distention better shows circumferential wall thickening with mucosal enhancement (arrow) and submucosal hypoenhancement (arrowhead), comprising the target sign, indicative of submucosal inflammation and edema. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image along the axis of the distal esophagus shows supradiaphragmatic positioning of the EGJ (straight arrow) with circumferential wall thickening of the distal esophageal wall, consistent with hiatal hernia and known reflux esophagitis. Note the presence of the target sign, composed of enhancing mucosa (curved arrow) and hypoenhancing submucosa (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Fast HASTE (half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo) T2-weighted image shows wall thickening of the distal esophagus (straight arrow) with high-signal-intensity mural edema (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig10c.jpeg" height="1465" width="1323" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows marked circumferential wall thickening (arrow), which is a nonspecific finding but correlates well with the presence of reflux esophagitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained with gaseous luminal distention better shows circumferential wall thickening with mucosal enhancement (arrow) and submucosal hypoenhancement (arrowhead), comprising the target sign, indicative of submucosal inflammation and edema. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image along the axis of the distal esophagus shows supradiaphragmatic positioning of the EGJ (straight arrow) with circumferential wall thickening of the distal esophageal wall, consistent with hiatal hernia and known reflux esophagitis. Note the presence of the target sign, composed of enhancing mucosa (curved arrow) and hypoenhancing submucosa (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Fast HASTE (half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo) T2-weighted image shows wall thickening of the distal esophagus (straight arrow) with high-signal-intensity mural edema (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig10d.jpeg" height="1465" width="1619" aria-labelledby="fig10d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10d</span>. Reflux esophagitis. <b>(a)</b> Axial nonenhanced CT image shows marked circumferential wall thickening (arrow), which is a nonspecific finding but correlates well with the presence of reflux esophagitis. <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image obtained with gaseous luminal distention better shows circumferential wall thickening with mucosal enhancement (arrow) and submucosal hypoenhancement (arrowhead), comprising the target sign, indicative of submucosal inflammation and edema. <b>(c)</b> Sagittal oblique contrast-enhanced CT image along the axis of the distal esophagus shows supradiaphragmatic positioning of the EGJ (straight arrow) with circumferential wall thickening of the distal esophageal wall, consistent with hiatal hernia and known reflux esophagitis. Note the presence of the target sign, composed of enhancing mucosa (curved arrow) and hypoenhancing submucosa (arrowhead). <b>(d)</b> Fast HASTE (half-Fourier acquisition single-shot turbo spin-echo) T2-weighted image shows wall thickening of the distal esophagus (straight arrow) with high-signal-intensity mural edema (curved arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig10d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig11a.jpeg" height="1208" width="1610" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span>. Peptic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows diffuse deposition of pink-stained fibrous tissue (curved arrows) in the splayed muscularis propria (straight arrow). There is lymphocytic infiltration of the lamina propria and epithelium (circle), which is now composed of glands containing goblet cells (arrowheads), indicative of chronic inflammation and intestinal metaplasia. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen shows a focal area of luminal narrowing (arrows) just above the squamocolumnar junction. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows a focal area of smooth narrowing (arrow) adjacent to nodular reddened mucosa, consistent with erosive esophagitis. Note the finger-like projections of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (*), consistent with areas of Barrett esophagus. <b>(d)</b> Prone single-contrast radiograph shows smooth concentric narrowing of the midesophagus (arrows) with a tiny outpouching of contrast material (intramural pseudodiverticulosis).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig11b.jpeg" height="1693" width="1045" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span>. Peptic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows diffuse deposition of pink-stained fibrous tissue (curved arrows) in the splayed muscularis propria (straight arrow). There is lymphocytic infiltration of the lamina propria and epithelium (circle), which is now composed of glands containing goblet cells (arrowheads), indicative of chronic inflammation and intestinal metaplasia. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen shows a focal area of luminal narrowing (arrows) just above the squamocolumnar junction. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows a focal area of smooth narrowing (arrow) adjacent to nodular reddened mucosa, consistent with erosive esophagitis. Note the finger-like projections of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (*), consistent with areas of Barrett esophagus. <b>(d)</b> Prone single-contrast radiograph shows smooth concentric narrowing of the midesophagus (arrows) with a tiny outpouching of contrast material (intramural pseudodiverticulosis).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig11c.jpeg" height="1207" width="1336" aria-labelledby="fig11c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11c</span>. Peptic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows diffuse deposition of pink-stained fibrous tissue (curved arrows) in the splayed muscularis propria (straight arrow). There is lymphocytic infiltration of the lamina propria and epithelium (circle), which is now composed of glands containing goblet cells (arrowheads), indicative of chronic inflammation and intestinal metaplasia. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen shows a focal area of luminal narrowing (arrows) just above the squamocolumnar junction. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows a focal area of smooth narrowing (arrow) adjacent to nodular reddened mucosa, consistent with erosive esophagitis. Note the finger-like projections of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (*), consistent with areas of Barrett esophagus. <b>(d)</b> Prone single-contrast radiograph shows smooth concentric narrowing of the midesophagus (arrows) with a tiny outpouching of contrast material (intramural pseudodiverticulosis).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig11c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig11d.jpeg" height="1693" width="1210" aria-labelledby="fig11d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11d</span>. Peptic stricture. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of the esophagus shows diffuse deposition of pink-stained fibrous tissue (curved arrows) in the splayed muscularis propria (straight arrow). There is lymphocytic infiltration of the lamina propria and epithelium (circle), which is now composed of glands containing goblet cells (arrowheads), indicative of chronic inflammation and intestinal metaplasia. (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photograph of a gross specimen shows a focal area of luminal narrowing (arrows) just above the squamocolumnar junction. <b>(c)</b> Endoscopic image shows a focal area of smooth narrowing (arrow) adjacent to nodular reddened mucosa, consistent with erosive esophagitis. Note the finger-like projections of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (*), consistent with areas of Barrett esophagus. <b>(d)</b> Prone single-contrast radiograph shows smooth concentric narrowing of the midesophagus (arrows) with a tiny outpouching of contrast material (intramural pseudodiverticulosis).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig11d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig12.jpeg" height="2495" width="2698" aria-labelledby="fig12" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12</span>. Barrett esophagus. Drawing of the esophagus shows superior migration of the EGJ (curved arrow) with disruption of the phrenoesophageal ligaments (straight arrow). The squamocolumnar junction extends above the level of the EGJ, with finger-like projections of velvety red mucosa reaching into the distal esophagus. The reddish mucosa corresponds histologically to transformation of the distal esophageal mucosa from the normal stratified squamous epithelium into an intestinal columnar epithelium (inset). (Reprinted, with permission, from Aletta Ann Frazier, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig12">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig13a.jpeg" height="1767" width="1598" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of a biopsy specimen shows partial replacement of the normal stratified squamous epithelium by columnar cells along the surface (curved arrow) and well-formed glands containing goblet cells (straight arrow) surrounded by an inflammatory infiltrate (arrowheads) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows progressive cytologic and architectural changes, from well-defined round or oval glands composed of cells containing round smooth similar-sized nuclei (straight arrow) to hyperbasophilic (darker) glands with increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio and loss of goblet cells (curved arrow), as seen in low-grade dysplasia. Note the persistence of inflammatory infiltrate (arrowhead) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows loss of nuclear polarity, with stacking of nuclei (straight arrow), and increasing architectural complexity, with distortion and cribriforming (lumen in lumen) of the glands (curved arrow). Note the presence of inflammatory infiltrate (arrowhead) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig13b.jpeg" height="1448" width="1549" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of a biopsy specimen shows partial replacement of the normal stratified squamous epithelium by columnar cells along the surface (curved arrow) and well-formed glands containing goblet cells (straight arrow) surrounded by an inflammatory infiltrate (arrowheads) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows progressive cytologic and architectural changes, from well-defined round or oval glands composed of cells containing round smooth similar-sized nuclei (straight arrow) to hyperbasophilic (darker) glands with increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio and loss of goblet cells (curved arrow), as seen in low-grade dysplasia. Note the persistence of inflammatory infiltrate (arrowhead) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows loss of nuclear polarity, with stacking of nuclei (straight arrow), and increasing architectural complexity, with distortion and cribriforming (lumen in lumen) of the glands (curved arrow). Note the presence of inflammatory infiltrate (arrowhead) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig13c.jpeg" height="1448" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph of a biopsy specimen shows partial replacement of the normal stratified squamous epithelium by columnar cells along the surface (curved arrow) and well-formed glands containing goblet cells (straight arrow) surrounded by an inflammatory infiltrate (arrowheads) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph shows progressive cytologic and architectural changes, from well-defined round or oval glands composed of cells containing round smooth similar-sized nuclei (straight arrow) to hyperbasophilic (darker) glands with increased nuclear-to-cytoplasmic ratio and loss of goblet cells (curved arrow), as seen in low-grade dysplasia. Note the persistence of inflammatory infiltrate (arrowhead) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.) <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows loss of nuclear polarity, with stacking of nuclei (straight arrow), and increasing architectural complexity, with distortion and cribriforming (lumen in lumen) of the glands (curved arrow). Note the presence of inflammatory infiltrate (arrowhead) and fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig14a.jpeg" height="1199" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a, b)</b> Endoscopic images show a short segment <b>(a)</b> and a longer segment <b>(b)</b> of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (curved arrow) extending cephalically from the EGJ, defined as the most proximal extent of the gastric folds. Note the normal smooth pale appearance of the normal squamous mucosa (*) and the refluxate within the small hiatal hernia (straight arrow in <b>a</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast esophagrams show short (arrow in <b>c</b>) and long smooth tapered (arrows in <b>d</b>) midesophageal strictures, the most specific radiographic finding for Barrett esophagus. Note the granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa <b>(c)</b> and the small hiatal hernia <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig14b.jpeg" height="1199" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a, b)</b> Endoscopic images show a short segment <b>(a)</b> and a longer segment <b>(b)</b> of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (curved arrow) extending cephalically from the EGJ, defined as the most proximal extent of the gastric folds. Note the normal smooth pale appearance of the normal squamous mucosa (*) and the refluxate within the small hiatal hernia (straight arrow in <b>a</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast esophagrams show short (arrow in <b>c</b>) and long smooth tapered (arrows in <b>d</b>) midesophageal strictures, the most specific radiographic finding for Barrett esophagus. Note the granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa <b>(c)</b> and the small hiatal hernia <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig14c.jpeg" height="2307" width="754" aria-labelledby="fig14c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14c</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a, b)</b> Endoscopic images show a short segment <b>(a)</b> and a longer segment <b>(b)</b> of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (curved arrow) extending cephalically from the EGJ, defined as the most proximal extent of the gastric folds. Note the normal smooth pale appearance of the normal squamous mucosa (*) and the refluxate within the small hiatal hernia (straight arrow in <b>a</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast esophagrams show short (arrow in <b>c</b>) and long smooth tapered (arrows in <b>d</b>) midesophageal strictures, the most specific radiographic finding for Barrett esophagus. Note the granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa <b>(c)</b> and the small hiatal hernia <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig14c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig14d.jpeg" height="2307" width="1095" aria-labelledby="fig14d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14d</span>. Barrett esophagus. <b>(a, b)</b> Endoscopic images show a short segment <b>(a)</b> and a longer segment <b>(b)</b> of salmon-colored velvety mucosa (curved arrow) extending cephalically from the EGJ, defined as the most proximal extent of the gastric folds. Note the normal smooth pale appearance of the normal squamous mucosa (*) and the refluxate within the small hiatal hernia (straight arrow in <b>a</b>). <b>(c, d)</b> Double-contrast esophagrams show short (arrow in <b>c</b>) and long smooth tapered (arrows in <b>d</b>) midesophageal strictures, the most specific radiographic finding for Barrett esophagus. Note the granular appearance of the distal esophageal mucosa <b>(c)</b> and the small hiatal hernia <b>(d)</b>.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig14d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig15a.jpeg" height="1425" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows the changes associated with progression to adenocarcinoma, with back-to-back irregularly shaped glands of varying size containing hyperchromatic nuclei (curved arrow) within the mucosa and infiltrating into the lamina propria and muscularis (straight arrow). Note the extensive fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images show flat mucosal nodules (arrow in <b>b</b>) on a background of Barrett esophagus (* in <b>b</b>) and a larger polypoid intraluminal mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) causing luminal narrowing. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic US image accurately shows the depth of tumor invasion. The hyperechoic tumor (*) disrupts alternating rings of hyperechoic superficial mucosa, hypoechoic deep mucosa, hyperechoic submucosa, and hypoechoic muscularis propria (arrowheads), with minimal extension into the hyperechoic adventitia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig15b.jpeg" height="1199" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows the changes associated with progression to adenocarcinoma, with back-to-back irregularly shaped glands of varying size containing hyperchromatic nuclei (curved arrow) within the mucosa and infiltrating into the lamina propria and muscularis (straight arrow). Note the extensive fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images show flat mucosal nodules (arrow in <b>b</b>) on a background of Barrett esophagus (* in <b>b</b>) and a larger polypoid intraluminal mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) causing luminal narrowing. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic US image accurately shows the depth of tumor invasion. The hyperechoic tumor (*) disrupts alternating rings of hyperechoic superficial mucosa, hypoechoic deep mucosa, hyperechoic submucosa, and hypoechoic muscularis propria (arrowheads), with minimal extension into the hyperechoic adventitia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig15c.jpeg" height="1199" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows the changes associated with progression to adenocarcinoma, with back-to-back irregularly shaped glands of varying size containing hyperchromatic nuclei (curved arrow) within the mucosa and infiltrating into the lamina propria and muscularis (straight arrow). Note the extensive fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images show flat mucosal nodules (arrow in <b>b</b>) on a background of Barrett esophagus (* in <b>b</b>) and a larger polypoid intraluminal mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) causing luminal narrowing. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic US image accurately shows the depth of tumor invasion. The hyperechoic tumor (*) disrupts alternating rings of hyperechoic superficial mucosa, hypoechoic deep mucosa, hyperechoic submucosa, and hypoechoic muscularis propria (arrowheads), with minimal extension into the hyperechoic adventitia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig15d.jpeg" height="1425" width="1575" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Photomicrograph shows the changes associated with progression to adenocarcinoma, with back-to-back irregularly shaped glands of varying size containing hyperchromatic nuclei (curved arrow) within the mucosa and infiltrating into the lamina propria and muscularis (straight arrow). Note the extensive fibrosis (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×100.) <b>(b, c)</b> Endoscopic images show flat mucosal nodules (arrow in <b>b</b>) on a background of Barrett esophagus (* in <b>b</b>) and a larger polypoid intraluminal mass (arrow in <b>c</b>) causing luminal narrowing. <b>(d)</b> Endoscopic US image accurately shows the depth of tumor invasion. The hyperechoic tumor (*) disrupts alternating rings of hyperechoic superficial mucosa, hypoechoic deep mucosa, hyperechoic submucosa, and hypoechoic muscularis propria (arrowheads), with minimal extension into the hyperechoic adventitia.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig16a.jpeg" height="1538" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast esophagrams show progression from initial to late manifestations of esophageal adenocarcinoma, from a small intraluminal polypoid mass with an ulcer (arrow in <b>a</b>) to a larger concentric irregular nodular mass narrowing the esophageal lumen (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Esophagram shows a malignant stricture, which can be differentiated from benign strictures by its irregular nodular contour (straight arrow) and abrupt margins (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig16b.jpeg" height="1538" width="1098" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast esophagrams show progression from initial to late manifestations of esophageal adenocarcinoma, from a small intraluminal polypoid mass with an ulcer (arrow in <b>a</b>) to a larger concentric irregular nodular mass narrowing the esophageal lumen (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Esophagram shows a malignant stricture, which can be differentiated from benign strictures by its irregular nodular contour (straight arrow) and abrupt margins (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig16c.jpeg" height="1538" width="1099" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast esophagrams show progression from initial to late manifestations of esophageal adenocarcinoma, from a small intraluminal polypoid mass with an ulcer (arrow in <b>a</b>) to a larger concentric irregular nodular mass narrowing the esophageal lumen (arrow in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Esophagram shows a malignant stricture, which can be differentiated from benign strictures by its irregular nodular contour (straight arrow) and abrupt margins (curved arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig17a.jpeg" height="1424" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images show wall thickening (* in <b>a</b>), involvement of surrounding fat planes (curved arrow), and adjacent lymph nodes (straight arrow in <b>a</b>); however, adequate luminal distention after ingestion of effervescents allows better depiction of enhancement and intraluminal projection (* in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal three-dimensional CT reconstruction shows a short-segment tight stricture (straight arrow) with abrupt margins (curved arrow) at the EGJ, causing cup-shaped distention of the proximal and mid esophagus with gas and ingested contents.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig17b.jpeg" height="1424" width="1574" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images show wall thickening (* in <b>a</b>), involvement of surrounding fat planes (curved arrow), and adjacent lymph nodes (straight arrow in <b>a</b>); however, adequate luminal distention after ingestion of effervescents allows better depiction of enhancement and intraluminal projection (* in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal three-dimensional CT reconstruction shows a short-segment tight stricture (straight arrow) with abrupt margins (curved arrow) at the EGJ, causing cup-shaped distention of the proximal and mid esophagus with gas and ingested contents.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig17c.jpeg" height="1547" width="1399" aria-labelledby="fig17c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17c</span>. Esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a, b)</b> Contrast-enhanced CT images show wall thickening (* in <b>a</b>), involvement of surrounding fat planes (curved arrow), and adjacent lymph nodes (straight arrow in <b>a</b>); however, adequate luminal distention after ingestion of effervescents allows better depiction of enhancement and intraluminal projection (* in <b>b</b>). <b>(c)</b> Sagittal three-dimensional CT reconstruction shows a short-segment tight stricture (straight arrow) with abrupt margins (curved arrow) at the EGJ, causing cup-shaped distention of the proximal and mid esophagus with gas and ingested contents.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig17c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig18" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig18.jpeg" height="1931" width="3000" aria-labelledby="fig18" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 18</span>. T staging of esophageal adenocarcinoma based on the eighth edition of the American Joint Committee on Cancer (AJCC) TNM system. T categories are determined by depth of invasion: Tis = high-grade dysplasia confined to the epithelium; T1 = cancer invades the lamina propria, muscularis mucosae, or submucosa; T2 = cancer invades the muscularis propria; T3 = cancer invades the adventitia; T4 = cancer invades adjacent structures and must be differentiated into T4a (invasion of nonvital structures, including the pleura, pericardium, diaphragm, peritoneum, or azygos vein) or T4b (invasion of vital structures, including the aorta, trachea, or vertebral body). (Reprinted, with permission, from Aletta Ann Frazier, MD.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig18">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig19a.jpeg" height="1446" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig19a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19a</span>. T3 esophageal adenocarcinoma in a 61-year-old man with progressive dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked circumferential and nodular wall thickening (curved arrow) causing luminal narrowing (*), with infiltration of the surrounding fat (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows nodular infiltration of the esophageal wall (curved arrows) with tumor extending to the surface (straight arrow). * = lumen. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumoral expansion of the wall (curved arrow) extending from the mucosal surface to the adventitial fat (straight arrow), causing luminal narrowing (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig19a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig19b.jpeg" height="1626" width="1155" aria-labelledby="fig19b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19b</span>. T3 esophageal adenocarcinoma in a 61-year-old man with progressive dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked circumferential and nodular wall thickening (curved arrow) causing luminal narrowing (*), with infiltration of the surrounding fat (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows nodular infiltration of the esophageal wall (curved arrows) with tumor extending to the surface (straight arrow). * = lumen. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumoral expansion of the wall (curved arrow) extending from the mucosal surface to the adventitial fat (straight arrow), causing luminal narrowing (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig19b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig19c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig19c.jpeg" height="1626" width="1797" aria-labelledby="fig19c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 19c</span>. T3 esophageal adenocarcinoma in a 61-year-old man with progressive dysphagia. <b>(a)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT image shows marked circumferential and nodular wall thickening (curved arrow) causing luminal narrowing (*), with infiltration of the surrounding fat (straight arrow). <b>(b)</b> Photograph of the gross specimen shows nodular infiltration of the esophageal wall (curved arrows) with tumor extending to the surface (straight arrow). * = lumen. <b>(c)</b> Photomicrograph shows tumoral expansion of the wall (curved arrow) extending from the mucosal surface to the adventitial fat (straight arrow), causing luminal narrowing (*). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×40.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig19c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig20" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig20.jpeg" height="1547" width="1400" aria-labelledby="fig20" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 20</span>. Stage IV esophageal adenocarcinoma. Coronal PET/CT image shows marked uptake in the primary esophageal tumor (straight arrow), right hilar and upper abdominal lymphadenopathy (curved arrow), and distant metastases in the lung (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig20">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig21a.jpeg" height="1198" width="1324" aria-labelledby="fig21a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21a</span>. Stage T3 esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows intermediate-signal-intensity tumor (arrows) replacing the normal layers of the esophageal wall and infiltrating through the muscularis propria, with blurring of the outer esophageal border. Arrowheads = intact muscularis propria along the posterior esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph matched to the same level shows tumor involving the submucosa and muscularis (arrows), with intact muscularis along the posterior wall (arrowheads). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×4.) (Case courtesy of Angela M. Riddell, MD, Royal Marsden Hospital, London, England.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig21a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig21b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2020190029/asset/images/large/rg.2020190029.fig21b.jpeg" height="1198" width="1325" aria-labelledby="fig21b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 21b</span>. Stage T3 esophageal adenocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> T2-weighted MR image shows intermediate-signal-intensity tumor (arrows) replacing the normal layers of the esophageal wall and infiltrating through the muscularis propria, with blurring of the outer esophageal border. Arrowheads = intact muscularis propria along the posterior esophagus. <b>(b)</b> Photomicrograph matched to the same level shows tumor involving the submucosa and muscularis (arrows), with intact muscularis along the posterior wall (arrowheads). (H-E stain; original magnification, ×4.) (Case courtesy of Angela M. Riddell, MD, Royal Marsden Hospital, London, England.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2020190029&amp;id=fig21b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Dent J, El-Serag HB, Wallander MA, Johansson S. Epidemiology of gastro-oesophageal reflux disease: a systematic review. <em>Gut</em> 2005;54(5):710–717.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1136/gut.2004.051821">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15831922/">PubMed</a></div><div class="